1
00:00:32,198 --> 00:00:35,036
- Come on, baby!
- Yes! What a shot! Nice one, Marty.

2
00:00:35,119 --> 00:00:37,079
The bank's open on Sunday.

3
00:00:37,162 --> 00:00:39,643
- The bank's open on Sunday.
- Hold it. Guys, guys, one moment.

4
00:00:43,545 --> 00:00:44,753
Come on, man!

5
00:00:45,255 --> 00:00:47,465
Hello? Yes.

6
00:00:52,679 --> 00:00:53,679
Okay.

7
00:00:54,472 --> 00:00:56,057
Come on. Hurry it up!

8
00:00:56,140 --> 00:00:57,850
Okay, thank you. Bye.

9
00:01:11,448 --> 00:01:14,367
- Everything okay?
- Yeah, my father's dead.

10
00:01:14,450 --> 00:01:16,890
- All right, ball in. Ball in. Let's go.
- Your father's dead?

11
00:01:16,953 --> 00:01:18,412
Yeah. Ball in, ball in.

12
00:01:18,495 --> 00:01:20,456
- What do you mean? Like dead, dead?
- Here we go.

13
00:01:39,475 --> 00:01:44,021
I knew as a toddler
that my father had lost his parents because I had no grandparents.

14
00:01:45,272 --> 00:01:51,528
I knew as a child he had lost his siblings
because I had no uncles or aunts.

15
00:01:52,530 --> 00:01:56,158
I only discovered as an adolescent
he had lost his wife.

16
00:01:57,953 --> 00:02:02,873
I only discovered as an adult
he had lost his child.

17
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:09,631
So when he got out of the camp,
he came here, having lost everything.

18
00:02:10,257 --> 00:02:14,385
We cannot truly mourn my father
without mourning his first wife.

19
00:02:14,468 --> 00:02:17,264
Without mourning my brother, Boruch.

20
00:02:21,643 --> 00:02:22,727
This was a great man.

21
00:02:27,566 --> 00:02:28,567
A he...

22
00:02:31,569 --> 00:02:33,572
A hero, if you will.

23
00:02:34,614 --> 00:02:42,622
I am nothing but grateful and humbled to be called Wolfgang Herschkopf's son.

24
00:02:45,207 --> 00:02:47,627
Dr. Herschkopf,
I'm so sorry for your loss.

25
00:02:48,211 --> 00:02:50,629
Your eulogy was amazing.

26
00:02:51,506 --> 00:02:52,966
Thank you. Thank you.

27
00:02:53,049 --> 00:02:54,718
- And thank you for coming.
- Yeah.

28
00:02:54,800 --> 00:02:56,427
- I'll see you Thursday?
- Of course.

29
00:02:56,510 --> 00:03:06,020
So I was thinking,
with the holiday coming up, well… I was just wondering if you guys would wanna come to the Hamptons house for Memorial Day weekend.

30
00:03:06,645 --> 00:03:09,566
Wow, that's very kind of you, Marty. I...

31
00:03:10,525 --> 00:03:13,277
Well, you know, we're a whole gang now.
I... I don't want to intrude.

32
00:03:13,360 --> 00:03:17,574
I would love to have the kids.
I mean, there's a pool. They could swim.

33
00:03:18,074 --> 00:03:21,661
Well, even so,
I'm not very good company right now.

34
00:03:21,745 --> 00:03:30,127
Sometimes when Shiva is over
and things go back to normal, it can be, you know, a more difficult time.

35
00:03:30,211 --> 00:03:37,760
I just thought… You might really enjoy being somewhere where you can relax and be taken care of.

36
00:03:38,344 --> 00:03:39,679
Maybe play some hoops.

37
00:03:40,639 --> 00:03:42,432
That's very thoughtful of you, Marty.

38
00:03:43,849 --> 00:03:45,310
Well, what do you think, chuch?

39
00:03:45,393 --> 00:03:48,729
I mean, the Hamptons, a pool.
I mean, the girls would love it.

40
00:03:49,313 --> 00:03:51,316
We'll cook. We'll hang out.

41
00:03:52,150 --> 00:03:54,902
I-I mean, I think it could be
really great for you, Dr. Ike.

42
00:03:54,985 --> 00:03:57,405
It does sound nice. A weekend.

43
00:03:57,489 --> 00:04:00,032
Well, you heard the lady. We accept.

44
00:04:00,116 --> 00:04:01,617
That's great.

45
00:04:01,700 --> 00:04:03,828
- Thank you, Marty.
- Absolutely.

46
00:04:04,329 --> 00:04:06,038
- Thank you, Marty.
- Not at all.

47
00:04:06,122 --> 00:04:08,917
I-It's the least I could do
after everything you've done for me.

48
00:04:23,055 --> 00:04:24,057
Wow.

49
00:04:32,356 --> 00:04:33,483
Hi, Marty.

50
00:04:33,567 --> 00:04:35,776
Hi, guys. Hi, girls.

51
00:04:35,860 --> 00:04:38,237
Leave the bags. Come on.
I'll show you around.

52
00:04:39,322 --> 00:04:42,242
- Ugh, I love this millwork.
- Oh, yeah.

53
00:04:42,324 --> 00:04:44,159
- Thank you.
- And all the nauticalia.

54
00:04:44,952 --> 00:04:46,579
- That's not a word.
- Come out here.

55
00:04:46,663 --> 00:04:48,581
I need you to see this. All right?

56
00:04:49,206 --> 00:04:50,207
Wow.

57
00:04:50,292 --> 00:04:51,918
Welcome. Make yourself at home.

58
00:04:52,002 --> 00:04:53,627
You have a beautiful property.

59
00:04:53,711 --> 00:04:56,798
Yeah, our Marty is a regular Jay Gatsby.

60
00:04:57,798 --> 00:04:59,091
And what kind of tree is that?

61
00:04:59,175 --> 00:05:01,720
Well, that's a cherry tree.
Yeah, it's been here forever.

62
00:05:01,802 --> 00:05:03,387
And how long have you been here, Marty?

63
00:05:03,471 --> 00:05:05,598
It's been in my family since the '50s.

64
00:05:05,682 --> 00:05:08,059
You're very lucky
to have inherited this place, Marty.

65
00:05:08,143 --> 00:05:11,396
Not everyone gets a house
in the Hamptons handed down to them.

66
00:05:11,478 --> 00:05:17,651
All my dad left me was
partial hearing in my right ear and a lot of polyester pants.

67
00:05:18,819 --> 00:05:21,156
So, how are you feeling?

68
00:05:22,281 --> 00:05:24,783
Not a question I often get
in my line of business.

69
00:05:24,867 --> 00:05:25,869
I bet you don't.

70
00:05:27,161 --> 00:05:28,163
I'm good.

71
00:05:28,872 --> 00:05:29,872
Thank you, friend.

72
00:05:30,456 --> 00:05:33,250
You wanna take a nap or go for a walk?

73
00:05:33,334 --> 00:05:34,793
Maybe some food?

74
00:05:34,877 --> 00:05:38,673
Think of me as your concierge.
I'm here to help with your every need.

75
00:05:38,757 --> 00:05:40,257
That's very kind of you, Marty.

76
00:05:40,341 --> 00:05:44,012
Very kind and unnecessary.
We... We're just thrilled to be here.

77
00:05:45,137 --> 00:05:48,516
And… here we are.

78
00:05:48,600 --> 00:05:51,478
Drumroll, please. The kitchen.

79
00:05:52,687 --> 00:05:56,441
Wow. Wow. Wow,
did we step into a time machine, huh?

80
00:05:56,524 --> 00:05:58,151
What is it, 1952 again?

81
00:05:58,235 --> 00:05:59,235
Ike.

82
00:05:59,319 --> 00:06:01,403
I'm kidding. I'm kidding.
It's part of our bit.

83
00:06:01,487 --> 00:06:05,533
It could use some updates, sure.
I guess I've just been busy.

84
00:06:05,617 --> 00:06:07,285
I understand that. It can be a lot.

85
00:06:09,411 --> 00:06:10,538
Is that your mom?

86
00:06:10,622 --> 00:06:13,124
- She was so pretty.
- Yeah.

87
00:06:13,708 --> 00:06:15,252
- And your dad.
- Uh-huh.

88
00:06:15,334 --> 00:06:17,211
He's so like you.

89
00:06:17,295 --> 00:06:18,672
You must miss them.

90
00:06:18,754 --> 00:06:21,507
- Mom, can I have a bagel?
- Goddamn it.

91
00:06:22,091 --> 00:06:23,802
They were a great-looking couple, Marty.

92
00:06:28,514 --> 00:06:31,560
But listen to me.
And I know this is tough to hear.

93
00:06:32,935 --> 00:06:35,396
You're not honoring them
by living in the past.

94
00:06:35,480 --> 00:06:38,066
I just buried my dad.
I know what I'm talking about.

95
00:06:38,149 --> 00:06:39,149
I know you do.

96
00:06:39,233 --> 00:06:44,613
They died ten years ago, Marty,
but this place is a... is a museum.

97
00:06:44,697 --> 00:06:48,451
Your parents would want you to be happy.
To enjoy your life.

98
00:06:48,534 --> 00:06:49,536
- Right?
- Sure.

99
00:06:49,619 --> 00:06:51,120
You've got to move on.

100
00:06:52,497 --> 00:06:55,709
If not for you, do it for them.

101
00:07:02,673 --> 00:07:04,884
Come on. Let's have a bite.

102
00:07:04,968 --> 00:07:08,430
All right. So here we have
the master bedroom.

103
00:07:08,512 --> 00:07:10,139
How charming.

104
00:07:10,682 --> 00:07:12,057
Wow! Look at this view.

105
00:07:12,141 --> 00:07:14,019
Wow, I love the Americana.

106
00:07:14,101 --> 00:07:16,187
- Where should we put our stuff?
- Well, it depends.

107
00:07:16,271 --> 00:07:19,649
There are two bedrooms in this house
and there's one bedroom in the guesthouse.

108
00:07:19,733 --> 00:07:21,401
Guesthouse? Fancy.

109
00:07:22,276 --> 00:07:24,653
You know what?
Why don't you guys stay here?

110
00:07:24,737 --> 00:07:28,324
What? No, that's crazy. We're not
kicking you out of the master bedroom.

111
00:07:28,408 --> 00:07:30,160
- I insist.
- Absolutely not.

112
00:07:30,242 --> 00:07:34,247
Marty, that's absurd. I'm sure
we can all squeeze into the guest bedroom.

113
00:07:34,331 --> 00:07:39,252
It makes sense. You guys are in here.
The girls are across the hall. It's fine.

114
00:07:39,336 --> 00:07:41,254
I'll sleep in the guesthouse
for the weekend.

115
00:07:41,338 --> 00:07:42,338
Really?

116
00:07:43,173 --> 00:07:47,302
Actually, it's not a bad idea.
The girls are up at the crack of dawn.

117
00:07:47,384 --> 00:07:48,511
That is true.

118
00:07:49,095 --> 00:07:50,805
All right. Then it's settled.

119
00:09:07,465 --> 00:09:08,466
Oh, no!

120
00:09:09,301 --> 00:09:13,638
I'm being attacked by sea monsters!
Help me!

121
00:09:13,721 --> 00:09:16,725
Well, I made you some iced coffee
if you manage to escape.

122
00:09:16,807 --> 00:09:18,807
- Their tentacles are so long!
- I'm gonna get you.

123
00:09:25,442 --> 00:09:26,650
You doing okay?

124
00:09:27,360 --> 00:09:28,528
Yeah, I'm okay.

125
00:09:31,030 --> 00:09:33,450
I feel at home here, you know, chuch?

126
00:09:34,366 --> 00:09:35,659
Feels right.

127
00:09:35,744 --> 00:09:37,495
It's so generous of Marty.

128
00:09:39,914 --> 00:09:41,332
Well, he invited us.

129
00:09:41,957 --> 00:09:44,919
- Yes! Great belly flop.
- He wants us here.

130
00:09:45,003 --> 00:09:47,588
You gotta learn to accept hospitality
with good grace.

131
00:09:47,672 --> 00:09:50,634
I mean, that's the key element
of being a good guest.

132
00:09:50,716 --> 00:09:52,677
No, it's just nice of him. That's all.

133
00:09:52,760 --> 00:09:56,514
Well, we're helping him out.
You know, he...

134
00:09:57,599 --> 00:10:00,976
You think he has fun
hanging around this old house by himself?

135
00:10:01,061 --> 00:10:03,270
I just don't want to take advantage,
you know?

136
00:10:03,355 --> 00:10:04,480
No, he's lonely, Bon.

137
00:10:05,190 --> 00:10:07,192
And what's the best treatment
for loneliness?

138
00:10:07,274 --> 00:10:08,735
I can throw you all day long.

139
00:10:08,817 --> 00:10:13,240
Company. Company is the best treatment.
I mean, look at him.

140
00:10:15,033 --> 00:10:17,118
- My turn, my turn!
- And throw!

141
00:10:17,826 --> 00:10:19,245
He's having a ball.

142
00:10:19,828 --> 00:10:21,956
He's laughing
for the first time in months.

143
00:10:22,791 --> 00:10:26,503
I'm not worried about Marty.
I'm worried about you.

144
00:10:27,836 --> 00:10:29,004
I'm fine.

145
00:10:29,088 --> 00:10:30,256
All right, you guys.

146
00:10:34,009 --> 00:10:36,929
- No, you can't. No, you can't. Get in!
- No, you can't.

147
00:10:43,061 --> 00:10:44,062
What's that?

148
00:10:45,020 --> 00:10:47,856
- I guess music?
- Are they having a party?

149
00:10:47,941 --> 00:10:50,485
No, it's a share-house.

150
00:10:50,568 --> 00:10:53,654
My neighbor rents it out over the summer
to cover the mortgage.

151
00:10:55,573 --> 00:10:57,951
Honey, come back.

152
00:11:00,035 --> 00:11:01,162
Honey, let it go.

153
00:11:12,506 --> 00:11:14,634
Wall Street idiots.
Think they own the place.

154
00:11:14,717 --> 00:11:17,888
I think they're just having fun.
You know, just like we are.

155
00:11:17,971 --> 00:11:20,599
And I actually kinda like that music.

156
00:11:20,682 --> 00:11:22,600
Just ignore them. That's what I do.

157
00:11:24,476 --> 00:11:26,730
No, you know what? Come on, Marty.
Let's go into town.

158
00:11:26,812 --> 00:11:29,065
- We'll get some provisions.
- What kind of provisions?

159
00:11:29,149 --> 00:11:32,985
You know. Some wine. Some meat.
A missile launcher. Kidding.

160
00:11:33,068 --> 00:11:34,153
- Really?
- Yeah.

161
00:11:34,236 --> 00:11:35,905
Don't you wanna just, you know, relax?

162
00:11:35,989 --> 00:11:38,825
No! No, I wanna show
these guys next door how it's done.

163
00:11:39,326 --> 00:11:41,620
- Let's go.
- All right. All right.

164
00:11:42,287 --> 00:11:44,748
- There, girls.
- Guys, don't be gone too long.

165
00:11:49,878 --> 00:11:50,879
Hi, Ken.

166
00:11:50,961 --> 00:11:52,923
Hey, Marty.

167
00:11:53,423 --> 00:11:58,177
Hi, Elise. I wanna introduce you
to my friend. This is Ike.

168
00:11:58,260 --> 00:11:59,346
Dr. Ike Herschkopf.

169
00:11:59,428 --> 00:12:01,722
Dr. Ike. Pleasure.

170
00:12:01,806 --> 00:12:03,390
We're just off to the beach club.

171
00:12:03,475 --> 00:12:05,809
Ken went crazy and bought a catamaran.

172
00:12:05,894 --> 00:12:10,315
I hope I can figure out how to sail it.
Next stop, France.

173
00:12:10,398 --> 00:12:12,442
- Have a lovely day.
- Bye-bye.

174
00:12:12,524 --> 00:12:15,653
Yeah, that's Ken.
He's the money guy for a lot of people.

175
00:12:15,736 --> 00:12:19,157
- Roy Scheider, I think. Yeah.
- He works with Roy Scheider?

176
00:12:19,240 --> 00:12:21,743
Uh-huh. He was with him
the last time I saw him.

177
00:12:21,826 --> 00:12:24,703
Yeah, Ken has tickets to the US Open.
Some box or other.

178
00:12:24,788 --> 00:12:26,498
It's not really my scene though.

179
00:12:31,503 --> 00:12:32,504
Roy Scheider.

180
00:12:36,423 --> 00:12:37,967
How long has Ken lived here?

181
00:12:38,051 --> 00:12:40,052
He's what we call "old money."

182
00:12:40,135 --> 00:12:41,136
How old?

183
00:12:41,221 --> 00:12:43,597
Gosh, I don't know. The Dutch?

184
00:12:45,432 --> 00:12:48,227
Here, you need these.
Your eyes are getting all red.

185
00:12:48,311 --> 00:12:51,940
Sea monsters, get ready for battle!

186
00:12:52,023 --> 00:12:54,567
- Honey. We're back.
- Yay!

187
00:12:55,150 --> 00:12:56,528
Time for a sundowner, I think.

188
00:12:56,610 --> 00:12:59,072
- Look at you.
- Yeah.

189
00:12:59,655 --> 00:13:00,823
I went to the store.

190
00:13:00,907 --> 00:13:03,158
- You look great.
- I feel great.

191
00:13:06,580 --> 00:13:08,581
Mom and Dad are kissing.

192
00:13:19,466 --> 00:13:21,094
Let's get the party started.

193
00:13:21,177 --> 00:13:22,428
Okay.

194
00:13:43,325 --> 00:13:46,201
So, I'm feeling like I'm making progress.

195
00:13:47,953 --> 00:13:49,581
Yeah. You are.

196
00:13:50,373 --> 00:13:54,336
You, as a person,
are making incredible progress.

197
00:13:54,919 --> 00:13:57,923
Now you need to do the same - for your environment. - What do you mean?

198
00:13:58,005 --> 00:14:00,258
Your home is
a reflection of your personality.

199
00:14:00,341 --> 00:14:07,640
As you become
more comfortable with yourself, as you become more authentic, more able to invite people in, you need to do the same with your home.

200
00:14:07,724 --> 00:14:08,933
My apartment?

201
00:14:09,017 --> 00:14:12,062
No, actually I was thinking
more the house in the Hamptons.

202
00:14:12,645 --> 00:14:15,105
You know? Make it a place you want to be.

203
00:14:15,190 --> 00:14:18,360
A place that other people want to be.
A place that's open, inviting.

204
00:14:19,402 --> 00:14:20,445
I don't know.

205
00:14:20,528 --> 00:14:27,159
With just a little bit of imagination
and a little bit of work, that place could be incredible, and much more of a reflection of where you're at now.

206
00:14:27,244 --> 00:14:28,995
Yeah, I guess.

207
00:14:29,078 --> 00:14:37,254
The kind of place
that people can arrive at from the city and just go, "Wow."

208
00:14:39,713 --> 00:14:43,342
Because you deserve it, Marty.
You do. You deserve it.

209
00:14:43,426 --> 00:14:45,386
Say it. "I deserve it."

210
00:14:47,681 --> 00:14:48,682
I deserve it.

211
00:14:48,764 --> 00:14:50,767
- Again.
- Again?

212
00:14:53,144 --> 00:14:54,144
I deserve it.

213
00:14:54,229 --> 00:14:55,230
Again.

214
00:14:56,313 --> 00:14:58,567
- "I deserve it." Again.
- I deserve it.

215
00:14:59,234 --> 00:15:01,653
- I deserve it. Again.
- I deserve it.

216
00:15:02,236 --> 00:15:04,072
- I deserve it.
- I deserve it.

217
00:15:04,572 --> 00:15:05,865
Feels good, doesn't it?

218
00:15:10,703 --> 00:15:13,289
- Look at this. The house next door…
- Right?

219
00:15:13,373 --> 00:15:15,500
- You know, jackass central?
- Yeah.

220
00:15:15,583 --> 00:15:17,376
- It's for sale.
- Okay.

221
00:15:17,460 --> 00:15:19,379
- You should buy that property.
- What?

222
00:15:19,461 --> 00:15:22,423
- You have to buy that property.
- I already have a house.

223
00:15:22,506 --> 00:15:25,384
Well, yeah, your parents' house,
but don't you want your own house?

224
00:15:25,467 --> 00:15:26,927
I mean, not really.

225
00:15:27,011 --> 00:15:29,722
Well, isn't that what every man dreams of?
His own castle.

226
00:15:29,806 --> 00:15:31,325
You should sell your house,
buy that house.

227
00:15:31,349 --> 00:15:32,909
- I don't think I need it.
- Marty. Excuse me.

228
00:15:32,933 --> 00:15:35,134
- Could I have a word?
- Bruce. We... He's in a meeting.

229
00:15:35,186 --> 00:15:37,956
Yeah, I have this month's accounts here,
and I'd like you to take a look at it.

230
00:15:37,980 --> 00:15:41,025
- Great. Leave them outside.
- Yeah. Thank you, Bruce. Thank you.

231
00:15:41,860 --> 00:15:42,860
We'll get to it.

232
00:15:43,570 --> 00:15:47,698
It's a much better house.
It's bigger. It has an amazing pool.

233
00:15:48,283 --> 00:15:49,533
I kind of prefer mine.

234
00:15:52,828 --> 00:15:54,748
Sure. Okay. Yeah, well.

235
00:15:55,373 --> 00:15:56,540
It's just a suggestion.

236
00:15:57,584 --> 00:15:58,960
I'll go to my office.

237
00:16:01,837 --> 00:16:04,633
But I thought
your idea to renovate was great.

238
00:16:04,716 --> 00:16:05,716
Really?

239
00:16:05,799 --> 00:16:09,888
Totally. I think it's
something we should really do.

240
00:16:09,971 --> 00:16:13,307
I'm ready.
I just don't know where to start.

241
00:16:13,390 --> 00:16:16,394
Well, I mean, I could show you.
If you want.

242
00:16:16,477 --> 00:16:17,687
I would love that.

243
00:16:18,312 --> 00:16:20,523
Would you and the girls come back
this weekend?

244
00:16:20,606 --> 00:16:23,902
Oh, no. No, no.
You should enjoy it on your own.

245
00:16:23,985 --> 00:16:27,029
But I don't enjoy it on my own. Come.

246
00:16:27,529 --> 00:16:29,783
Please. We could at least make a start.

247
00:16:29,865 --> 00:16:33,577
You sure you don't mind spending
another weekend in the guesthouse?

248
00:16:35,413 --> 00:16:37,624
I'm beginning to think
maybe you prefer it in there.

249
00:16:38,457 --> 00:16:39,459
It's fine.

250
00:16:43,754 --> 00:16:44,755
Wow.

251
00:16:46,799 --> 00:16:47,926
I'm gonna chase you.

252
00:16:48,969 --> 00:16:50,595
Yeah, okay.

253
00:16:55,307 --> 00:16:58,562
Hey, see how much fresher
it feels already?

254
00:16:58,644 --> 00:16:59,729
It's like a new beginning.

255
00:17:00,230 --> 00:17:01,230
Yeah.

256
00:17:01,898 --> 00:17:03,857
I think I might keep this one.

257
00:17:04,401 --> 00:17:06,111
Sure. Yeah, of course.

258
00:17:07,237 --> 00:17:08,404
Whatever you want.

259
00:17:11,949 --> 00:17:14,702
Hey, let's have some fun.

260
00:17:49,863 --> 00:17:51,323
In my testicles.

261
00:17:51,405 --> 00:17:54,409
Ike, Ike, that's a low blow.

262
00:17:56,786 --> 00:17:58,579
You are something else.

263
00:17:58,663 --> 00:18:00,915
- You started it.
- You're a can of beans.

264
00:18:01,665 --> 00:18:04,126
Hey, you know, I was thinking.

265
00:18:05,670 --> 00:18:11,800
What if, instead of selling this property, you bought the place next door and combined the two properties?

266
00:18:12,426 --> 00:18:23,730
Look, what if you… Okay, what if you put in a beautiful tennis court and then, just next to that, a basketball court?

267
00:18:24,230 --> 00:18:25,773
Then you got a little seating area.

268
00:18:25,856 --> 00:18:28,026
- Uh-huh.
- Behind that, like, a bar.

269
00:18:28,108 --> 00:18:29,443
You've got a bigger pool.

270
00:18:29,527 --> 00:18:33,490
And look at this.
There's room for a miniature golf course.

271
00:18:34,406 --> 00:18:35,659
- Uh-huh.
- Yeah.

272
00:18:35,741 --> 00:18:38,161
All you have to do,
you clear out that area.

273
00:18:38,244 --> 00:18:44,291
Get rid of that tree, and you've added
$250,000 to your property overnight.

274
00:18:44,875 --> 00:18:47,962
You know, I have a patient who's
a tree guy. You should give him a call.

275
00:18:48,046 --> 00:18:51,007
I'm not cutting down that tree. Ever.

276
00:18:51,090 --> 00:18:52,550
What? What do you mean?

277
00:18:52,634 --> 00:18:55,554
My parents planted that tree
when they bought the house.

278
00:18:56,887 --> 00:18:59,598
Phyllis and I used to climb on it
when we were younger.

279
00:18:59,682 --> 00:19:01,518
Then her kids used to climb on it.

280
00:19:01,601 --> 00:19:05,063
My mom actually used to talk to the tree.

281
00:19:06,189 --> 00:19:10,067
She used to get up every morning
and say, "Good morning, tree."

282
00:19:11,486 --> 00:19:12,695
She loved that tree.

283
00:19:13,821 --> 00:19:17,032
Sounds weird. I love that tree.

284
00:19:19,868 --> 00:19:23,163
Your mother talked to a tree.
Did it answer?

285
00:19:23,248 --> 00:19:25,208
I don't know. Maybe.

286
00:19:28,545 --> 00:19:29,546
Hey.

287
00:19:29,628 --> 00:19:30,630
Hey, what is it?

288
00:19:31,673 --> 00:19:32,923
Come on. Let's keep painting.

289
00:19:38,805 --> 00:19:44,227
You know, anytime you wanna talk
about your dad, or anything.

290
00:19:45,353 --> 00:19:46,438
That's very sweet.

291
00:19:47,271 --> 00:19:52,359
But, to quote you, "I'm fine."

292
00:19:53,612 --> 00:19:57,156
I just mean, you know, you've always said,
"It's okay to not be okay."

293
00:19:57,240 --> 00:19:58,950
You must miss him.

294
00:19:59,034 --> 00:20:05,664
Listen, Marty. Between you and me,
he wasn't much of a father.

295
00:20:06,499 --> 00:20:09,376
He was a great man, not a great dad.

296
00:20:10,628 --> 00:20:12,130
- I'm so sorry.
- Don't be.

297
00:20:14,924 --> 00:20:19,637
I've made peace with it, 'cause I know that he loved me with every cell of his body.

298
00:20:19,721 --> 00:20:20,721
Of course he did.

299
00:20:20,805 --> 00:20:23,307
He just couldn't show me his love.

300
00:20:23,391 --> 00:20:26,310
I can forgive him and let it go.

301
00:20:31,316 --> 00:20:33,067
God, I love it here, Marty.

302
00:20:33,567 --> 00:20:35,528
I wish you didn't have to leave
tomorrow night.

303
00:20:36,028 --> 00:20:37,113
Me too.

304
00:20:37,822 --> 00:20:42,285
You know, something about nature
has me reevaluating my life.

305
00:20:42,952 --> 00:20:45,329
I've taken a dance with my creative self.

306
00:20:47,039 --> 00:20:48,959
I've been working on a novel.

307
00:20:49,625 --> 00:20:51,336
- That's great.
- It is great.

308
00:20:51,419 --> 00:20:57,342
And I feel like I need to maybe
take a time out and focus on that.

309
00:20:59,594 --> 00:21:00,720
I need a break.

310
00:21:01,887 --> 00:21:03,390
I need some space.

311
00:21:06,351 --> 00:21:08,353
Space? From what?

312
00:21:08,435 --> 00:21:10,063
Space from everything, you know?

313
00:21:13,107 --> 00:21:18,654
I feel like going somewhere
and just sitting and writing awhile.

314
00:21:18,738 --> 00:21:20,990
Really? Where?

315
00:21:21,074 --> 00:21:26,246
I don't know.
Maybe Jerusalem. I love it there.

316
00:21:27,454 --> 00:21:29,332
I feel like it's calling me.

317
00:21:30,208 --> 00:21:33,336
And I would get to do an aliyah,
which is something I've wanted to do.

318
00:21:33,420 --> 00:21:36,256
What do you me...
I'm sorry, it just... It's all so...

319
00:21:37,089 --> 00:21:42,804
Look, I love the idea
that you wanna take the time to do this, but Jerusalem?

320
00:21:42,887 --> 00:21:46,849
It just seems crazy to go all that way
when everything you need is right here.

321
00:21:46,932 --> 00:21:49,310
Here? But this is your place, Marty.

322
00:21:49,394 --> 00:21:51,605
Ours. It's ours. We're family, remember?

323
00:21:51,688 --> 00:21:54,441
No, no. I wouldn't want to feel like
I'm getting in your way.

324
00:21:54,523 --> 00:21:56,108
No. No, no, no. No. Absolutely not.

325
00:21:56,192 --> 00:21:59,278
Because if I feel like I'm in your way,
it's very blocking to me.

326
00:21:59,362 --> 00:22:01,041
How can you say that?
It would be an honor.

327
00:22:01,071 --> 00:22:03,575
I feel the need to be
in a supportive environment.

328
00:22:03,657 --> 00:22:05,760
It would be supportive.
It would be so supportive here.

329
00:22:05,785 --> 00:22:08,078
I would love to help you
plot out the book.

330
00:22:08,163 --> 00:22:11,708
You could clear your head,
and get your creative juices flowing.

331
00:22:11,790 --> 00:22:13,000
It would be a win-win.

332
00:22:15,961 --> 00:22:16,962
I don't know.

333
00:22:20,759 --> 00:22:22,635
I'd have to think about it, Marty.

334
00:22:26,765 --> 00:22:28,307
Please... Please stay.

335
00:22:38,734 --> 00:22:39,736
Okay.

336
00:22:41,238 --> 00:22:44,782
We'll send Bonnie and the kids
back to the city tomorrow, and then we'll start work.

337
00:22:45,532 --> 00:22:47,285
Okay. Good.

338
00:22:50,747 --> 00:22:51,748
Thank you.

339
00:22:54,960 --> 00:22:57,586
Goodbye, my favorite sea monsters.

340
00:22:57,671 --> 00:23:00,131
- Bye, Uncle Marty.
- Bye, Uncle Marty.

341
00:23:00,214 --> 00:23:02,008
Marty, don't lead him astray.

342
00:23:02,092 --> 00:23:03,509
I make no promises.

343
00:23:04,344 --> 00:23:05,345
- Bye.
- Bye.

344
00:23:06,179 --> 00:23:08,973
So, I'll see you… couple weeks?

345
00:23:09,057 --> 00:23:10,808
Well, we'll have to see.

346
00:23:11,518 --> 00:23:17,858
My patients know
I'm on a short sabbatical, so… - Okay. - But I'm sure we'll have you back as soon as the first draft is done. Right, Marty?

347
00:23:17,941 --> 00:23:18,942
Absolutely.

348
00:23:19,025 --> 00:23:21,486
Okay, well, have fun, you guys.

349
00:23:21,569 --> 00:23:23,320
We're not having fun. We're working.

350
00:23:23,404 --> 00:23:24,990
Okay, that's what I meant.

351
00:23:28,576 --> 00:23:30,077
- Bye, girls.
- Bye, Dad.

352
00:23:30,161 --> 00:23:31,328
Miss you already.

353
00:23:32,079 --> 00:23:34,415
Hey, don't work too hard, okay?

354
00:23:34,499 --> 00:23:36,939
'Cause I know how you get
when you're going through something.

355
00:23:37,251 --> 00:23:39,712
- Please don't play therapist with me.
- I'm just saying.

356
00:23:39,796 --> 00:23:43,215
You keep saying you're fine,
but I'm not sure that you are.

357
00:24:02,152 --> 00:24:03,153
Marty.

358
00:24:04,487 --> 00:24:05,654
What? Is everything okay?

359
00:24:05,739 --> 00:24:07,656
Yeah, yeah, yeah. It's time to wake up.

360
00:24:07,740 --> 00:24:09,742
What? What time is it?

361
00:24:10,743 --> 00:24:11,869
Time to start work.

362
00:24:15,582 --> 00:24:17,584
Okay. All right.

363
00:24:17,666 --> 00:24:22,505
He knocked and slowly pushed open
the door to her boudoir.

364
00:24:24,924 --> 00:24:32,348
There she sat in front of the mirror, slowly applying lipstick to her mouth.

365
00:24:33,892 --> 00:24:36,769
Dusty pink. Parisian, possibly.

366
00:24:36,853 --> 00:24:38,020
"Parisian.

367
00:24:39,689 --> 00:24:41,732
- Possibly."
- "You were right," he said.

368
00:24:41,816 --> 00:24:44,818
"The body was there as you described.

369
00:24:45,569 --> 00:24:49,406
Under the bridge.
One brogue on the left foot."

370
00:24:49,490 --> 00:24:54,037
"One brogue on the left foot."

371
00:24:54,119 --> 00:24:58,083
"But you didn't kill him."
"How do you know?" she asked.

372
00:24:59,084 --> 00:25:01,461
I was just going to ask the same thing.

373
00:25:04,172 --> 00:25:05,214
He cou...

374
00:25:06,924 --> 00:25:10,511
No, no, no. Let it go. Let it go.

375
00:25:10,595 --> 00:25:13,347
- No, I better, just in case.
- Don't stop the flow.

376
00:25:14,682 --> 00:25:17,894
- Hello.
- Hey, Marty, it's Bruce. How you doin'?

377
00:25:17,978 --> 00:25:20,980
- I'm fine. Thank you, Bruce.
- For God's sake.

378
00:25:22,106 --> 00:25:23,400
Can we talk about AFC?

379
00:25:23,482 --> 00:25:25,402
- Not now, we're working.
- Not now, Bruce.

380
00:25:25,484 --> 00:25:26,736
You know what? We'll talk soon.

381
00:25:26,819 --> 00:25:28,180
- I promise.
- Yeah, bu... Marty...

382
00:25:30,281 --> 00:25:32,491
- Sorry, Ike.
- Where were we?

383
00:25:34,786 --> 00:25:35,787
Focus.

384
00:26:17,412 --> 00:26:26,837
Then all of a sudden… Wait, wait. And I... You know what?

385
00:26:31,509 --> 00:26:34,596
Marty! Hey, Marty! Come over.
Come over and meet my new friends.

386
00:26:36,263 --> 00:26:38,807
I gave him a new offer.
Do the right thing. Anyway.

387
00:26:40,434 --> 00:26:43,355
Marty! Come here. Come here.
You gotta meet everybody.

388
00:26:43,438 --> 00:26:48,526
This is Marcus, Brock,
Kingsley and Lennox.

389
00:26:48,609 --> 00:26:51,070
All their names are surnames.
It's hilarious.

390
00:26:51,654 --> 00:26:53,073
Hi, good to meet you.

391
00:26:53,155 --> 00:26:54,365
- Hey, Marty.
- Hey, Marty.

392
00:26:55,200 --> 00:27:00,263
These guys are the best.
They've been working 75-hour weeks, and now they're finally taking a well-deserved break.

393
00:27:00,288 --> 00:27:02,082
- Am I right? Am I right?
- Hell yeah!

394
00:27:03,333 --> 00:27:04,541
How about this place, huh?

395
00:27:05,417 --> 00:27:07,503
It's somethin' else. Yeah.

396
00:27:07,586 --> 00:27:10,423
See that barbecue?
It's bigger than your house.

397
00:27:10,507 --> 00:27:12,092
Super big. Yeah.

398
00:27:12,592 --> 00:27:14,385
And how about this pool, huh?

399
00:27:14,469 --> 00:27:16,887
Kidney-shaped. You can't go wrong.

400
00:27:16,971 --> 00:27:21,058
I dare you to strip off and jump in.
Totally naked. Yeah? Come on!

401
00:27:21,142 --> 00:27:24,688
Do it! Do it! Do it!

402
00:27:24,770 --> 00:27:26,730
You know, I'm... I'm too sweaty.

403
00:27:26,815 --> 00:27:28,107
- Sweaty?
- Come on, Marty.

404
00:27:28,191 --> 00:27:30,086
- Come on.
- You don't want my sweat in your pool.

405
00:27:30,109 --> 00:27:31,295
- Come jump in.
- Come on in, Marty.

406
00:27:31,318 --> 00:27:33,113
Look, I-I would love to, I just...

407
00:27:33,195 --> 00:27:36,407
I'm in the middle of a bunch of stuff,
and I better get back to it.

408
00:27:36,490 --> 00:27:38,826
- Marty.
- Nice to meet you.

409
00:27:38,910 --> 00:27:41,538
- Yeah.
- You just got here. Look. Marty!

410
00:27:42,247 --> 00:27:43,664
Marty, come on!

411
00:27:44,249 --> 00:27:46,125
Such a joy thief.

412
00:27:46,209 --> 00:27:50,005
Sorry, guys. Think I'd better
get back to my own personal hell.

413
00:27:51,631 --> 00:27:53,799
Still, it was nice to be out on day leave.

414
00:27:59,388 --> 00:28:03,809
By the way, if you could just turn
the music down a jot.

415
00:28:03,894 --> 00:28:06,896
I love it, but I think
Marty might be on his period.

416
00:28:06,980 --> 00:28:08,230
Poor Marty!

417
00:28:09,566 --> 00:28:10,567
Later.

418
00:28:11,151 --> 00:28:12,234
Top me off.

419
00:28:12,318 --> 00:28:14,653
What a bunch of fucking pricks.

420
00:28:15,154 --> 00:28:18,616
- Those guys?
- Entitled hedge fund scum.

421
00:28:18,700 --> 00:28:19,826
I can't stand 'em.

422
00:28:19,910 --> 00:28:23,329
The good news is the owner is
going through a really nasty divorce.

423
00:28:23,413 --> 00:28:24,413
- Oh, no.
- Yeah.

424
00:28:24,497 --> 00:28:26,333
He needs to sell quick.

425
00:28:26,415 --> 00:28:29,419
So you could probably offer,
like, less, and he'd have to take it.

426
00:28:29,501 --> 00:28:30,502
Poor Bob.

427
00:28:30,586 --> 00:28:32,172
You should call your Realtor.

428
00:28:33,423 --> 00:28:34,924
- I don't know.
- Are you crazy?

429
00:28:35,008 --> 00:28:36,884
You'd have the best house in Southampton.

430
00:28:39,054 --> 00:28:40,888
It's about the tree, isn't it?

431
00:29:07,832 --> 00:29:10,085
- Turn left.
- This is an adventure.

432
00:29:10,751 --> 00:29:12,253
It is. It is.

433
00:29:12,336 --> 00:29:14,648
- Okay, straight. Straight.
- Okay, right. Still going straight.

434
00:29:14,673 --> 00:29:16,924
- You're going to turn right. Now…
- And now?

435
00:29:17,759 --> 00:29:19,553
- I feel dizzy.
- Do you know where you are?

436
00:29:19,635 --> 00:29:21,262
I can't even begin to guess.

437
00:29:21,346 --> 00:29:24,974
- Okay, now. Stop. I'm just...
- Yep. What?

438
00:29:25,057 --> 00:29:26,308
- Okay.
- Yeah.

439
00:29:27,394 --> 00:29:29,311
Okay, open your eyes.

440
00:29:32,022 --> 00:29:36,861
Yeah, you will never have to look at
that blueberry hellhole again.

441
00:29:36,944 --> 00:29:39,154
- Never again.
- Never again.

442
00:29:39,864 --> 00:29:41,407
There's holes in the wall.

443
00:29:41,490 --> 00:29:42,616
It's on its way.

444
00:29:43,242 --> 00:29:45,744
- It's gonna be... I have this vision.
- Yeah.

445
00:29:45,828 --> 00:29:48,539
All that monochromatic nonsense.

446
00:29:48,623 --> 00:29:53,127
You know what? This is where
my parents used to measure Phyllis and me.

447
00:29:53,211 --> 00:29:54,796
Oh, my gosh.

448
00:29:55,380 --> 00:29:58,215
Isn't it funny to think about?
I-I was only that tall.

449
00:29:58,299 --> 00:30:04,096
Oh, my gosh. That was the summer
that Phyllis really shot up, - and I-I-I was so jealous. - They're dead.

450
00:30:05,598 --> 00:30:08,684
- What?
- Marty, you have to let them go.

451
00:30:08,768 --> 00:30:12,314
I swear, this house,
it's not a museum. It's a tomb.

452
00:30:14,356 --> 00:30:18,962
You know, sometimes I feel like
I'm working on you, but I don't think you're working on you. Do you know what I'm saying?

453
00:30:18,987 --> 00:30:23,032
I'm sorry. I'm sorry.
I promise, I'll work harder.

454
00:30:24,409 --> 00:30:25,492
Don't be mad at me.

455
00:30:25,576 --> 00:30:27,746
I'm not mad. I'm just...

456
00:30:29,079 --> 00:30:30,498
Marty, relax.

457
00:30:31,875 --> 00:30:34,169
Yeah, breathe.
It's not good for your heart.

458
00:30:36,378 --> 00:30:40,049
It's gonna be great.
It's not done. It's gonna be great.

459
00:30:40,133 --> 00:30:41,218
- Trust me.
- Okay.

460
00:30:58,734 --> 00:31:01,988
So, I just got off the phone
with the Realtor.

461
00:31:02,071 --> 00:31:04,199
- Really? What did he say?
- Bad news.

462
00:31:04,281 --> 00:31:05,659
How do you mean?

463
00:31:05,741 --> 00:31:08,494
He says under no circumstances
should anyone buy that house.

464
00:31:08,577 --> 00:31:10,955
It needs underpinning,
and the septic tank has never worked.

465
00:31:11,455 --> 00:31:12,582
Why would he say that?

466
00:31:14,125 --> 00:31:16,169
You know what?
He wants to buy the house himself.

467
00:31:16,252 --> 00:31:19,923
Oh, no. No. He's an old family friend.
He's just trying to give me a heads-up.

468
00:31:20,006 --> 00:31:23,425
Bullshit. He knows you're sitting
on a gold mine, and he wants a piece.

469
00:31:23,509 --> 00:31:24,719
I don't think so.

470
00:31:25,595 --> 00:31:26,721
He's lying, Marty.

471
00:31:26,805 --> 00:31:29,432
Now, look, we need to move quickly.
Have you called the tree guy?

472
00:31:30,432 --> 00:31:31,518
No.

473
00:31:31,601 --> 00:31:32,602
Why not?

474
00:31:34,688 --> 00:31:36,565
What is it with you and that fucking tree?

475
00:31:37,065 --> 00:31:40,818
I don't know.
I guess it just has sentimental value.

476
00:31:40,902 --> 00:31:43,488
Sentimental val... Did this tree raise you?

477
00:31:44,573 --> 00:31:45,406
No.

478
00:31:45,490 --> 00:31:49,411
No? Did this tree change your diaper?
Did it cook you a meal?

479
00:31:49,493 --> 00:31:50,744
Did it pay for your school?

480
00:31:51,328 --> 00:31:53,539
That's not really what I'm trying to say.

481
00:31:53,623 --> 00:31:56,292
What are you saying?
Are you in love with the tree?

482
00:31:57,210 --> 00:32:01,839
Marty, you told me years ago
you'd never been in love, but you failed to mention that you're in love with a tree.

483
00:32:01,923 --> 00:32:02,923
I'm just fond of it.

484
00:32:03,008 --> 00:32:05,343
Fond? Fond how? Like, sexually?

485
00:32:06,303 --> 00:32:09,431
Because it's sounding an awful lot to me
like maybe you want to fuck this tree.

486
00:32:10,848 --> 00:32:12,182
I don't want to fuck the tree.

487
00:32:14,477 --> 00:32:15,478
I'm joking.

488
00:32:21,317 --> 00:32:25,614
I just feel like, if anyone has a thing
about the tree, it's you.

489
00:32:26,196 --> 00:32:29,116
I said I didn't want to chop it down,
and you won't let it go.

490
00:32:29,200 --> 00:32:32,828
For some reason,
it feels like you hate this tree.

491
00:32:36,665 --> 00:32:39,711
So, the lunatics have taken over
the asylum, have they?

492
00:32:40,420 --> 00:32:42,297
You're psychoanalyzing me?

493
00:32:42,380 --> 00:32:44,673
No. No, no. I just... I don't understand...

494
00:32:44,758 --> 00:32:46,175
No, you don't understand, Marty.

495
00:32:47,344 --> 00:32:48,845
But let me see if I can help you.

496
00:32:50,055 --> 00:32:54,058
Your feelings about this tree
are not healthy.

497
00:32:55,769 --> 00:32:57,561
And it's all to do with your mother.

498
00:32:57,645 --> 00:33:03,567
The way your mother loved you
was not healthy, and that is a deep root of your pathology.

499
00:33:03,652 --> 00:33:08,990
A Freudian would say
that this tree is your mother's phallus.

500
00:33:09,074 --> 00:33:13,619
A big, looming totem
of her inappropriate desire for you.

501
00:33:14,203 --> 00:33:15,538
- That's not...
- Yes.

502
00:33:15,622 --> 00:33:18,916
Or it's her birth canal
trying to suck you back in.

503
00:33:20,042 --> 00:33:26,215
Your mother wouldn't let you grow up, and now she has left you emotionally and sexually stunted.

504
00:33:26,298 --> 00:33:28,009
And it is a fucking tragedy!

505
00:33:28,093 --> 00:33:29,553
Please stop.

506
00:33:30,135 --> 00:33:32,513
I know. I know, Marty. It's hard.

507
00:33:32,596 --> 00:33:36,142
The truth is hard,
but it is the only way you will heal.

508
00:33:38,811 --> 00:33:42,648
I love you properly. I won't hurt you.

509
00:33:43,148 --> 00:33:47,069
I will make sure
you blossom like this tree.

510
00:33:49,739 --> 00:33:50,740
Okay.

511
00:33:57,872 --> 00:33:59,290
I know. I know.

512
00:34:03,586 --> 00:34:04,837
So, what are you gonna do?

513
00:34:11,344 --> 00:34:12,344
I don't know.

514
00:34:15,014 --> 00:34:18,559
Even now? I thought we just looked
into your heart and your soul.

515
00:34:18,643 --> 00:34:20,163
I thought we had a breakthrough there.

516
00:34:22,230 --> 00:34:24,309
- Am I just wasting my time?
- No. No, of course not.

517
00:34:24,356 --> 00:34:26,356
You know what?
Maybe I'm just a terrible therapist.

518
00:34:26,400 --> 00:34:27,693
No, no. You're not.

519
00:34:27,777 --> 00:34:31,989
No, I think I might be
a terrible therapist because obviously, you have not moved on at all.

520
00:34:33,742 --> 00:34:35,869
- You know, maybe I should just give up.
- No.

521
00:34:35,952 --> 00:34:37,286
Great... Yes. Great idea.

522
00:34:37,369 --> 00:34:39,914
I give up on you,
and I give up on therapy.

523
00:34:40,498 --> 00:34:42,373
No, it's all right. Don't worry.

524
00:34:42,458 --> 00:34:45,378
I'm going to pack my bags,
and I'm gonna get out of your life.

525
00:36:40,076 --> 00:36:42,494
Why is Pearl even here?
He wasn't her father.

526
00:36:42,579 --> 00:36:44,831
Yeah, but he raised her,
and she loved him.

527
00:36:46,123 --> 00:36:48,501
I didn't think I had any tears left.

528
00:36:48,585 --> 00:36:50,085
It's good to let it come out.

529
00:36:50,836 --> 00:36:52,463
What did Wolf used to say?

530
00:36:53,088 --> 00:36:55,759
He'd say, "Mom's leaking again."

531
00:36:56,509 --> 00:37:01,431
Or, "You two better drink some water.
You're about to cry yourselves thirsty."

532
00:37:07,144 --> 00:37:08,313
How you doing?

533
00:37:08,396 --> 00:37:09,731
I'm fine, Mom.

534
00:37:09,813 --> 00:37:11,398
I know this is hard for ya.

535
00:37:11,483 --> 00:37:13,150
No. It's actually easy.

536
00:37:14,568 --> 00:37:16,780
- Ike.
- No. I'm free of trying to please him.

537
00:37:16,862 --> 00:37:18,864
Trying to please a man
who couldn't show love.

538
00:37:18,949 --> 00:37:20,282
Honey, listen to me.

539
00:37:20,367 --> 00:37:21,742
So, it's a good thing.

540
00:37:21,826 --> 00:37:24,161
He wanted to so much.

541
00:37:25,871 --> 00:37:27,123
Not enough.

542
00:37:27,706 --> 00:37:32,711
After losing Boruch, he couldn't dare
let himself love another son.

543
00:37:32,795 --> 00:37:35,215
You can understand that, can't you?

544
00:37:38,050 --> 00:37:39,052
No.

545
00:37:59,114 --> 00:38:01,615
So, I have some news.

546
00:38:02,409 --> 00:38:04,452
The sale went through, finally.

547
00:38:07,204 --> 00:38:08,998
So I own both properties.

548
00:38:11,458 --> 00:38:12,878
Congratulations.

549
00:38:12,960 --> 00:38:16,630
Called a contractor to rip down the fence.

550
00:38:16,715 --> 00:38:17,923
Nah, let's just do it now.

551
00:38:18,592 --> 00:38:19,842
Let's get it done.

552
00:38:54,168 --> 00:38:55,336
Jesus.

553
00:39:01,635 --> 00:39:02,635
You all right?

554
00:39:06,931 --> 00:39:08,516
We should have a party.

555
00:39:09,726 --> 00:39:11,268
A housewarming party.
